{"id":"2105.06404","submitter":"Matthias Bolten","authors":"Matthias Bolten and Jan Hahne","title":"Using ODE waveform-relaxation methods to efficiently include gap\n  junctions in distributed neural network simulations","comments":"9 pages, 11 figures","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.NA cs.NA","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Waveform-relaxation methods divide systems of differential equations into\nsubsystems and therefore allow for parallelization across the system. Here we\npresent an application for ODE waveform-relaxation methods in the context of\nspiking neural network simulators. Parallel spiking neural network simulators\nmake use of the fact that the dynamics of neurons with chemical synapses is\ndecoupled for the duration of the minimal network delay and thus can be solved\nindependently for this duration. The inclusion of electrical synapses,\nso-called gap junctions, requires continuous interaction between neurons and\ntherefore constitutes a conceptional problem for those simulators. We present a\nsuitable waveform-relaxation method for an efficient integration of gap\njunctions and demonstrate that the use of the waveform-relaxation method\nimproves both, accuracy and performance, compared to a non-iterative solution\nof the problem. We investigate the employed method in a reference\nimplementation in the parallel spiking neural network simulator NEST.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 13 May 2021 16:28:53 GMT"}],"update_date":"2021-05-14"}
